-- Sub-Saharan Africa Stocks: Omnicane, KenolKobil Move
-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 2011-12-23T11:54:06Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-23/sub-saharan-africa-stocks-omnicane-kenolkobil-move.html
Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index (SEMDEX)  advanced
for a third day, rising 0.5 percent to 1,869.76 by the end of
trading in  Port Louis , the capital.  Kenya’s  All-Share Index (NSEASI)  added 0.4 percent to 54.74 by 12:59
p.m. in Nairobi, a third day of gains. The  Nigerian Stock
Exchange All-Share Index (NGSEINDX)  rose for a sixth day, advancing less
than 0.1 percent to 20,617.68 by 11 a.m. in Lagos. Namibia’s
 FTSE/Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  gained 0.4 percent to 840.42 by 11:02
a.m. in Windhoek. The  Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index  slid
4.4 percent to 923.88, its biggest fall in a week, by 10:01 in
Accra.  The following are among the active equities in sub-Saharan
Africa, excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  KenolKobil Ltd. (KNOC)  , a fuel retailer with operations
in nine African countries, advanced for a fourth day, adding 4.2
percent to 9.90 shillings. Oil headed for its biggest weekly
gain in almost two months in New York after U.S. economic
reports indicated that growth in the world’s biggest crude
consumer will accelerate.  Omnicane Ltd. (MTMD)  , a Mauritian sugar producer with
interests in energy, rose to a three-week high, climbing 3.5
percent to 73.5 rupees. The company will pay a dividend of 2.75
rupees a share for the year through December, it said in a
 statement  to the Mauritius Stock Exchange today.  To contact the reporters on this story:
Stephen Gunnion in Johannesburg at 
